{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> φαίνω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 7.102, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>Epic dialect</i> also <b>φαείνω</b> (which see):—<i>future</i> φᾰνῶ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 304.5, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 827, etc. (φᾱνῶ _accusative_ to 2nd c.AD: Apollonius Dyscolus Grammaticus “de Adverbiis;” 187.26, but φᾱνῶ, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 300, and ἀναφᾱνῶ, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 528, are uncertain)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Ionic dialect</i> φᾰνέω (ἀπο-) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “Steril.” 213\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <i>optative</i> φᾰνοίην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 313 (codex recentia, rightly)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist 1</i> ἔφηνα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.318, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.95, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Doric dialect</i> ἔφᾱνα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 4(3).2, “IG” 42(1).123.28 (Epid., 4th c.BC), also later _Attic dialect_, \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>subjunctive</i>, ἀπο-φάνῃ uncertain reading in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 22.1631.379 (= 2.811c133)\">Refs</a>]; φάνῃς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Philemo Comicus 233 (ἐκ-φάνῃς 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus “Μονόστιχοι - Fragmenta Comicorum Graecorum” 418 = 4th-3rd c.BC: Chares Iambographus 4b20)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; so in late Prose, (ἐξ-) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “Varia Historia” 12.33, (ἐπι-) NT.Luke.1.79, (ἀνα-) NT.Act.21.3 \">NT+2nd c.AD+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>iterative</i> φάνεσκε (<i>intransitive</i>) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.64, +others, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Fragmenta” 14.3 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> πέφαγκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Pseudo-Callisthenes Historicus 2.10, (ἀπο-) 4th-3rd c.BC: Dinarchus Orator 1.15, +others: _intransitive_ \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<i>perfect</i> πέφηνα (see. below[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"A  111.2)\">Refs</a>], <i>Doric dialect</i><i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ἐκ-πεφάναντι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophron Comicus 83 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>pluperfect</i> ἐπεφήνειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 46.10 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, <i>future</i> <i>infinitive</i> φᾰνεῖσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.230 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>Ionic dialect</i> φᾰνέομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.35; _optative_ φανοῖσθε 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 26.10 (nisi to be read φανεῖσθε)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; the forms φανῆσθον and <i>Doric dialect</i> <i>imperative</i> φάνευ are corrupt in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Eryxias” 399e, 3rd c.BC: Teles Philosophus p.58 H. (to be read φαίνευ): \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist 1</i> ἐφηνάμην (<i>transitive</i>) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 944, (ἀπ-) 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.52, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>Ionic dialect</i> <i>imperfect</i> φαινέσκετο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.194 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> φᾰνήσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.108, Sicilian _Doric dialect_ (_infinitive_) φᾰνήσειν (perhaps -ησεῖν) 3rd c.BC: Archimedes Geometra “A ren.” 4.20; _Epic dialect_ \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>future</i> πεφήσεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.155 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist 1</i> ἐφάνθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 263 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 525, etc.:rare in Prose, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 6.4.11, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 58.13, (ἀπο-) “IG” 12.10.35, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.44 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> φαάνθη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.650 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> φάανθεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.200: \">Refs</a>]<i>aorist 2</i> ἐφάνην [ᾰ], <i>Epic dialect</i> φάνην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.477, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> φάνεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.68 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>subjunctive</i> φανήῃ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.375 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>infinitive</i> φανήμεναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.240 \">Refs</a>]: <i>perfect</i> πέφασμαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1543 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> πέφανται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.122, 16.207, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 5.115, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 374 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; πέφᾰται in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 9.52, Perictione Philosophus cited in 5th c.AD: Stobaeus, Joannes 4.28.19 belongs either to φαίνω in sense 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus 1.5\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], or to φημ; <i>infinitive</i> πεφάνθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 294a, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> πεφασμένος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.127, 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 227, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 843, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1122, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 245e, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> <i>pluperfect</i> ἐπέφαντο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 166. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__A</b></Level1> <i>active</i>, <b>bring to light, cause to appear,</b> in physical sense, τέρας τινὶ φ. <b>make</b> a sign <b>appear</b> to one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.324, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.173, etc.; σήματα φαίνων 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.353; γένυσι φ. ὀπώραν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 5.6; δύο μορφὰς φ. 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 304.5; τὸν αὐχένα 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.132 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἔφην᾽ ἄφαντον φῶς, i.e. fire, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 297; λαμπάδας 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 1524 (_anapaest meter_); φ. θησαυρόν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 565 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φ. μηρούς, ἐπιγουνίδα, <b>show by baring,</b> i.e. <b>uncover</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.67, 74; φαίνοισα πρόσωπον ἀλάθεια 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 5.17 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <b>reflect</b> an image in water, τὰ δέ νιν καλὰ κύματα φαίνει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 6.11:\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] —<i>middle</i>, τὰ τόξα.. τοῖσιν Ἀργείοισι φήνασθαι θέλει <b>exhibit</b> them <b>as his own,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 944. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__b</b></Level4> <b>make known, reveal, disclose,</b> ἐς τὸ φῶς φανεῖ κακά [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OT” 1229; κακῶν ἔκλυσιν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Taurica” 898 (Lyric poetry, probably); τὸν μιαρὸν τῷ χρόνῳ ἀποδόντες φῆναι 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 4.4.11; ὁδόν τινι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.334; τὰ ὀνείρατα καὶ τὸν πόρον 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 4.3.13, compare “Cyr.” 6.4.13, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 725; τοῖς πολεμίοις σύνθημα 4th-3rd c.BC: Dinarchus Orator 3.10, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φανεῖ.. κωκύματα wailings <b>will show forth</b> [the truth of what I say], [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 1078: with a predicate added, ἡμᾶς σὺ δειλοὺς φανεῖς\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] wilt <b>make</b> us <b>appear</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Aj.” 1362; τὸν Ααΐου φόνον φανεῖ δικαίως ὀρθόν [prev. author] “OT” 853. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__c</b></Level4> γόνον Ἑλένῃ φ. <b>show</b> her a child, i. e. <b>grant</b> her to bear one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.12 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φ. παράκοιτίν τινι <b>show</b> (i.e. <b>give</b>) one a wife, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 15.26. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of sound, <b>make</b> it <b>clear</b> to the ear, <b>make</b> it <b>ring clear,</b> ἀοιδὴν φαίνειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8.499; σάλπιγξ.. ὑπέρτονον γήρυμα φαινέτω στρατῷ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 569. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <b>show forth, display</b> in action, ἀρετήν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.237; ἀεικείας 20.309; βίην 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 689; εὐμαχανίαν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 4(3).2; εὔνοιαν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.36 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὕβριν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 127; ὀργάς 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 326 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__3.b</b></Level4> <b>set forth, expound,</b> νοήματα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.295; λόγον 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.116; τριφασίας λόγων ὁδούς [prev. author] 1.95 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; but τὰ λαμπρὰ.. φ. ἔπη <b>make</b> them <b>good,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 721. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> <b>inform against</b> one, <b>denounce,</b> φανῶ σε (σε φανῶ codices) τοῖς πρυτάνεσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 300 (Lyric poetry), compare “Ach.” 824, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 325 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <b>denounce</b> a thing <b>as contraband,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 542, 819, +others; φαίνειν πλοῖον 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 58.9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰ φανθέντα articles <b>denounced</b> as contraband, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 13: _absolutely_, \">Refs</a>]<b>give information,</b> ὁ φήνας ἢ ὁ γραψάμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 12.45.3, compare 4.24, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 18.20, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.2.14, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 2.207 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> φαίνειν φρουράν, <b>call up</b> a levy, at Sparta, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 3.2.23, +others\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also φ. θυσίαν <b>proclaim, order</b> a sacrifice, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Philodamus Scarpheus Lyricus 112:\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] —<i>passive</i>, πέφαται θνατοῖσι νίκας ὕστερον εὐφροσύνα has been <b>ordained,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 9.52. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>absolutely</i>, <b>give light, shine,</b> φαίνοντες νύκτας.. δαιτυμόνεσσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 7.102, compare 19.25 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of the sun, moon, etc., φ. τινί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 586 (troch.); εἰς ἅπαντα φ. τὸν οὐρανόν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 39b; ἀλλά, σελάνα, φαῖνε καλόν 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 2.11; οἱ λύχνοι φ. ἧττον 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Igne” 11 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; compare φάω: so ἦρι μὲν φαίνοντι in spring <b>when it shines forth,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 304.4 codices (to be read φανέντι)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; of the Dioscuri <b>shining</b> in mid-air, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 1234 (_anapaest meter_): _metaphorically_, ἀγανὴ φαίνουσ᾽ ἐλπίς\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] soft <b>shining</b> hope, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 101 (_anapaest meter_, uncertain). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.b</b></Level4> Φαίνων, οντος, ὁ, the planet <b>Saturn,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Mundo” 392a23, 1st c.BC: Cicero, M. Tullius Orator et Philosophus “de Natura Deorum” 2.20.52, etc.; Φ. ὁ τοῦ Ἡλίου 4th c.BC: Eudoxus Astronomus “Ars astronomica” 5.19 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; <i>accusative</i> <b>-ωνα</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Placita Philosophorum” 2.15.4. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>iterative</i> φάνεσκε <b>appeared,</b> μετὰ πρώτοισι φάνεσκε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.64; ὑπένερθε δὲ γαῖα φάνεσκε 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.242, compare 11.587, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Fragmenta” 14.3. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> <i>perfect</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2 πέφηνα is also used _intransitive_, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 328, etc.; less frequently in Prose, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.120, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 3.22, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 9.13.8. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> <i>passive</i>, <b>come to light, appear,</b> φάνεν δέ οἱ εὐρέες ὦμοι, being stripped bare, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.68, compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 22.324, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.39 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: frequently of fire, <b>shine brightly,</b> πυρὰ φαίνετο Ἰλιόθι πρό [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.561; ἕκαθεν δέ τε φαίνεται αὐγή 2.456; δεινὼ δέ οἱ ὄσσε φάανθεν \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<b>shone like fire,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.200 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: frequently of the <b>rising</b> of heavenly bodies, ἄστρα φαεινὴν ἀμφὶ σελήνην φαίνετ᾽ ἀριπρεπέα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8.556, compare 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 598 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of the first <b>gleam</b> of daybreak, ἦμος δ᾽ ἠριγένεια φάνη ῥοδοδάκτυλος Ἠώς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.477, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.1, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἅμ᾽ ἠοῖ φαινομένηφι at <b>break</b> of day, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.618, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.407, +others; ἀκτὶς ἀελίου, τὸκάλλιστον.. φανὲν.. τῶν προτέρων φάος, ἐφάνθης ποτ᾽ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 100 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: of a <b>rising</b> wind, οὐδέ ποτ᾽ οὖροι πνείοντες φαίνονθ᾽ ἁλιαέες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.361 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of a vapour, ἐκ νεφέων ἐρεβεννὴ φ. ἀήρ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.864. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.2</b></Level3> of persons, οἴῳ φαινομένη <b>appearing</b> to him alone, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.198, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.517, etc.; ἐφάνη λὶς εἰς ὁδόν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.275 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; οὗπερ κἀφάνης where <b>thou didst first appear,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 77; χρόνιος φανείς [prev. author] “Ph.” 1446 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὁδόν φανῆναι a pregnant expression for ἐλθεῖν ὁδὸν ὥστε φανῆναι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “El.” 1274 (Lyric poetry); κέλευθον φανείς “Aj.” 878 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]; πόθεν φαίν; whence <b>come you?</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 309a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.8.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐδαμοῦ φ. <b>is</b> nowhere <b>to be seen,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “An.” 1.10.16. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.2.b</b></Level4> <b>come into being,</b> φανεὶς δύστηνος <b>born</b> to misery, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 974, compare 1225 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>become,</b> ἐκ βασιλέως ἰδιώτην φανῆναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 7.7.28; δυοῖν ἐφάνη τριήραρχος 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.104 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>to be made out,</b> δοῦλος λόγοισιν.. φανείς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1020, compare 1241. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.3</b></Level3> of events, <b>come about,</b> τέλος οὔ πώ τι πέφανται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.122; φάνη βιότοιο τελευτή 7.104 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἔργον, ἄεθλον, etc.,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 16.207, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 21.106, etc.; τὸ φανθέν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 743 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of sayings, <b>to be set forth,</b> λόγος ἀρχαῖος φανείς[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 1, compare “OT” 474 (Lyric poetry), 848. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.II</b></Level2> <b>appear to be</b> so and so, with <i>infinitive</i>, δμῳάων ἥ τίς τοι ἀρίστη φαίνεται εἶναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.25, compare 11.336; οὐ γάρ σφιν ἐφαίνετο κέρδιον εἶναι 14.355; τοῦτό μοι θειότατον φαίνεται γενέσθαι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.137; εὖ σὺ λέγειν φαίνει 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 403 (_anapaest meter_), compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 319, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: frequently with <i>infinitive</i> omitted, οὗ καὶ πρόσθεν ἀρίστη φαίνετο βουλή [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.94, compare 2.5; ὅς τις φαίνηται ἄριστος 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.106; σμερδαλέος αὐτῇσι φάνη 6.137; ἕρμαιον ἂν ἐφάνη 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 368d, etc.: but in 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus, etc., \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] also with <i>participle</i>, <b>to be manifest</b>: thus, ἐμοὶ σὺ πλουτέειν μέγα φαίνεαι you <b>appear</b> to me to be very rich, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.32 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but εὔνοος ἐφαίνετο ἐών he was <b>manifestly</b> well-inclined, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 7.173, compare 175, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.2 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐκ ἄκαιρα φαίνεται λέγειν he <b>appears</b> to be speaking.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 1036 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; but φανέονται λέγοντες οὐδέν it <b>will be manifest</b> that they talk nonsense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.35; φαίνομαι δύο καθορᾶν εἴδη 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 235d; but οὐκ ἂν φανεῖμεν πήματ᾽ ἔρξαντες 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 786; πλαγκτὸς οὖσ᾽ ἐφαινόμην [prev. author] “Ag.” 593, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.89, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 343; ἐφάνησαν πεπονθότες 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 22c: with \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>participle</i> omitted, πέφανται ἁρματηλάτας σοφός (i.e. ὤν) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 5.115, compare “N.” 6.14; κρατηθεὶς ἡμερώτερος φανεῖ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1632 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Κᾶρες ἐφάνησαν (i.e. ὄντες) <b>they were seen</b> to be Carians, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τί φαίνομαι (i.e. ὤν) δῆτ; what <b>do I look like?</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 925; ὡς ἀγαθοὶ.. ἐφάνησαν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 408a: hence φαίνεσθαι, opposed to εἶναι, εἶναι μὲν ὅσπερ εἰμί, φαίνεσθαι δὲ μή 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 698 (cited in 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 441); στρατηγὸς ἀγαθὸς μὴ ὢν φαίνεσθαι 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.7.3; ὀλίγοι καὶ ὄντες καὶ φαινόμενοι [prev. author] “HG” 6.5.28. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.2</b></Level3> in Philosophy, φαίνομαι (<i>absolutely</i>) is sometimes used of what <b>appears</b> to the senses, φαίνεται δ᾽ οὐδὲν <b>is observed,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Physica” 204b35, compare “Cael.” 312b30; φ. κατὰ τὴν αἴσθησιν [prev. author] “GA” 716a31 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: sometimes of what <b>is</b> mentally <b>manifest,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “EN” 1175a29 \">Refs</a>]; <b>to be evident,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “APr.” 24b24 \">Refs</a>]: especially <b>appear</b> to the imagination [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (φαντασία 2), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 264b; φ. καὶ μύουσιν ὁράματα 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Anima” 428a16; φ. δέ τι.. οἷον τὰ ἐν τοῖς ὕπνοις [prev. work] a7: distinguished from αἰσθάνεσθαι and δοξάζειν, [prev. work] b1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: especially in <i>participle</i> φαινόμενος, η, ον: <br /><Level4><b>__B.II.2.a</b></Level4> <b>appearing</b> in sense experience, τὰ φ. κατὰ τὴν αἴσθησιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Cael.” 303a22, +others; εἴτε τὰ δοκοῦντα πάντα ἐστὶν ἀληθῆ καὶ τὰ φ. [prev. author] “Metaphorical” 1009a8, compare “de An.” 404a29 (_sing._); τὰ φ. \">Refs</a>]<b>sense-data,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “PA” 639b8, 4th-3rd c.BC: Epicurus Philosophus “Epistulae” 1pp.9,10 U., +others: Astron., τὰ φ.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] = celestial <b>phenomena,</b> title of a work by Eudoxus, versified by Aratus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Hipparchus Astronomicus 1.1.8, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Caelo” 293b27; πρός τινας δόξας αὑτῶν τὰ φ. προσέλκοντες [prev. work] 293a26 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: generally, τὸ μὴ ἐκ φαινομένων τὸ βλεπόμενον γεγονέναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Heb.11.3. \">NT</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.II.2.b</b></Level4> mentally <b>apparent,</b> opposed to ὄντα τῇ ἀληθείᾳ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 596e, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Topica” 100b24, “EN” 1113a24; τὰ οὖν ἐμοὶ φαινόμενα οὕτω φαίνεται 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 517b; [νοῦς] τῶν φ. θειότατον 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 1074b16 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ φ. εἰπεῖν to express one's <b>opinion,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.158c\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: hence, <b>specious, fallacious,</b> φ. ἐνθυμήματα, opposed to ὄντα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1402a28. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.II.2.c</b></Level4> τὰ φ. <b>what is to be seen, show,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Libanius Sophista “Orationes” 30.28. \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.3</b></Level3> frequently in answers in Plato's dialogue, φαίνεται, <b>yes, Prt.</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 332e, “R.” 333c, +others; ὥς γέ μοι φ. “Prt.” 324d, compare “R.” 383a, +others\">Refs</a>]: [τοῦτο] φῂς εἶνα; Answ. φαίνομαι (i.e. λέγειν) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 4.2.20. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.II.3.b</b></Level4> later <i>impersonal</i> with <i>dative</i> <i>person</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, <b>it seems good,</b> ἐάν σοι φαίνηται Wilcken [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Chr.” 304.11 (3rd c.BC),compare “PCair.Zen.” 44.7, 16 (3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>], etc.; ὁπότε αὐτῷ φανείη στρατιὰν ἐξάγειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 2.14, compare 4.85. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.4</b></Level3> joined with δοκέω, εἰ δὴ κακός τε φ. δοκῶ τέ σοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 1071; δοκοῖμεν ἂν.. χείρους φαίνεσθαι 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.122, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 269d, “Erx.” 399c, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.22. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.5</b></Level3> οὐδαμοῦ φαίνεσθαι 'to be nowhere', <i>metaphorically</i> from racing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 72c, compare “Grg.” 456b, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.310. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.III</b></Level2> τὰ φανθέντα, see above [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus 1.4. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5316","accentedUnicode":"φαίνω","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0852","matchingForm":"ἀφανής","stepTransliteration":"afanēs","gloss":"hidden","_zh_tw_Gloss":"不顯然","_es_Gloss":"oculto","_zh_Gloss":"不显然"},{"strongNumber":"G0855","matchingForm":"ἄφαντος","stepTransliteration":"afantos","gloss":"disappearing","_zh_tw_Gloss":"不見了","_es_Gloss":"que desaparece","_zh_Gloss":"不见了"},{"strongNumber":"G5318","matchingForm":"φανερός","stepTransliteration":"faneros","gloss":"clear","_zh_tw_Gloss":"顯明","_es_Gloss":"obvio","_zh_Gloss":"显明"},{"strongNumber":"G5322","matchingForm":"φανός","stepTransliteration":"fanos","gloss":"torch","_zh_tw_Gloss":"燈籠","_es_Gloss":"antorcha","_zh_Gloss":"灯笼"},{"strongNumber":"G5457","matchingForm":"φῶς","stepTransliteration":"fōs","gloss":"light","_zh_tw_Gloss":"光","_es_Gloss":"luz","_zh_Gloss":"光"}],"shortDef":"(act.) to shine, give light; (<i>middle</i>/<i>passive</i>); to appear, be visible;","mediumDef":"(act.) to shine, give light; (<i>middle</i>/<i>passive</i>); to appear, be visible; <br /><b>to cause to appear, bring to light;</b>, <i>absolute</i> <b>to shine, give light</b> <ref='Jhn.1.5; 5:35'>Jn. 1:5; 5:35</ref>; <ref='2Pe.1.19'>2Pet. 1:19;</ref> <ref='1Jn.2.8'>1Jn. 2:8;</ref> <ref='Rev.1.16'>Rev. 1:16;</ref> 8:12; 21:23; <i>middle</i>/<i>passive</i> <b>to be seen, appear, be visible,</b> <ref='Mat.1.20; 2:7, 13, 19'>Mt. 1:20; 2:7, 13, 19</ref>; <greek>τὰ φαινόμενα</greek>, <b>things visible, things obvious to the senses,</b> <ref='Heb.11.3'>Heb. 11:3;</ref> <greek>φαινομαι</greek>, <b>to appear, seen, be in appearance,</b> <ref='Mat.23.27'>Mt. 23:27</ref>; <ref='Luk.24.11'>Lk. 24:11</ref>; <b>to appear</b> in thought, <b>seen</b> in idea, <b>be a notion,</b> <ref='Mrk.14.64'>Mk. 14:64</ref>","stepGloss":"to shine/appear","stepTransliteration":"fainō","count":31,"_es_Definition":"brillar, dar luz, iluminar (voz media: FIL.2:15) ; voces media y pasiva: aparecer, ser visto, ser o volverse visible, ser revelado (ROM.7:13) ; aparentar ser algo, aparentar ; parecer, aparecer ; ¿qué pasará con el pecador? (1PE.4:18)","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 照亮, 閃亮<br>2) 出現, 顯現, 成為可見的<br>3) 被認出, 被顯示, 被顯明<br>4) 看起來是 (與實情相反)<br>4) 看起來, 似乎 (可 14:64)<br>7","_zh_Definition":"1) 照亮, 闪亮<br>2) 出现, 显现, 成为可见的<br>3) 被认出, 被显示, 被显明<br>4) 看起来是 (与实情相反)<br>4) 看起来, 似乎 (可 14:64)<br>7","_step_Type":"verb","_vi_Definition":"toả sáng; chiếu soi; hiện ra","_zh_tw_Gloss":"顯現","_es_Gloss":"brillar/aparecer","_zh_Gloss":"显现"}]}